<font color="#FF0000">WHAT WOULD IT HAVE REALLY TOOK</font><br>
<tt>Fri May  9  3:44:31 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Have been reading a variety of posts since February asserting that the war should have/could have been won; if only we took this action or that, or didn't make mistakes A through Z.  This has been bugging me for quite some time, and I finally decided it was time to fish or cut bait.<br><br>
One of Clausewitz's basic principles is that war is an extension of politics by other means.  While Sun Tzu considers the greatest success to win an objective without fighting a battle; most of the time the &quot;other means&quot; involves the controlled application of violence in the pursuit of political objectives.  <br><br>
Tactical victories don't always guarantee strategic success.<br>
Just take a look at the British during the American Revolution.  Howe beat Washington several times, but couldn't put him out of business.  Pyrrhus in Greece beat all comers, but didn't know how to convert his victories into anything concrete.<br><br>
The point being that I have yet to see any &quot;victory&quot; scenario that considers what is required for a permanent, stable peace on our terms, assuming we win.  I remember Tanker saying that all you had to do was just destroy the forests, and Voila!, no guerillas.  Even with all the defoliation with Agent Orange over the years, there was still quite a bit of forest left.  To get rid of the rest would have required an effort that would have probably destroyed the environment of most of Indochina.  Then there would be a hostile border with China, plus a need to occupy the place for 2 generations at least.<br><br>
If somebody has an idea of how a tactical victory could have been made into a complete strategic one leading to a stable peace on US terms; I'd like to hear it.  Otherwise, let's quit the pipe dreams.  The more I see and hear both on site and here in Philly; the more I'm convinced that it leads to a neverending search for &quot;them&quot; that &quot;betrayed&quot; the troops. Sometimes I've heard or read gripes that sound too much for comfort like the German Army's gripe, after WWI, that it was &quot;stabbed in the back&quot;.  God knows, we all were led down the primrose path on Vietnam, but substituting a new set of illusions for those destroyed isn't healthy for any of us or the country as a whole.<br><br>
I still remember a conversation that Col. Harry Summers had with a North Vietnamese counterpart of his some years back.  Summers told him that they never beat us on the battlefield. The other agreed, but then said, &quot;It's also irrelevant.&quot;<br><br>

